node.text:
“Why not??” Wednesday feature! The details on this are just gorgeous! 🤩 Be sure to swipe for a view of the stairway windows! 💘 Thanks for tagging #archi_ologie Posted @withregram • @godzilla1950 At 470 E Chicago St…another unique Stick Style house of Elgin. This one was completed in 1887 for stone cutter Arwin E. Price. Aside from being a successful businessman, owning a marble & granite works, Price pursued a political career as well, becoming mayor of Elgin in 1889. He would run for that office off /on for the next 30 yrs well into the early 1920’s. Price was dubbed the “Drunken Mayor” not for having a drinking problem, but for his highly entertaining political antics during his career. Sounds like he would be a perfect fit just for today’s political arena! 😉

The Price house is such a delightful example of that style. Charming details abound on it. I love the gazebo style downstairs porch and the dazzling woodwork of the upstairs porch! Plus the staircase stained glass windows are a sweet touch. Great paint job as well, but I yearn to see a touch of a contrasting warm color for more visual effect. The 2,400 sq ft house is still privately owned. #stickstylearchitecture #stickstyle #stickstylehouses #victorian #victorianhouse #victorianarchitecture #victorianstyle #archi  #archilovers #archilove #archidaily #housestalker #houseaddict #oldhouselove #curbappeal #stainedglass #oldhouseenthusiast #iloveoldhouses #thisoldhouse  #historichouse #houseportrait  #beautifulhouseoldandnew #houses_phototrip #arkitektur #oldhousecharm  #houseoftheday

Acorn Hall was built by whiskey distiller, William Squibb in 1883. The architect included both Romanesque and Italianate elements. The house became dilapidated, and faced foreclosure but @indianalandmarks helped  new owners aquire the property who restored it to its original grandeur.

node.text:
#mansardmonday 
The elusive convex #mansardroof Sooo pretty!
#Repost - @h_indiana by @get_regrammer
This is known as the Wing House - named for its second owner, Lucius  Wing. However, it was actually built for newlyweds Jay Chandler and Frances Campbell. Frances was from New York and was apparently reluctant to move to the less settled ‘’wild’ frontier of Coldwater, Michigan. So a replica of her home back east was built for her to ease the transition. When I first read this I thought maybe she was coming from NYC but it appears she came from a small town upstate on the Finger Lakes - actual upstate! In any case, she did not last long in Coldwater and took her husband back east and that is when the Wing’s moved in.

node.text:
Sunday Funday 🌞 Never tire of seeing this house in our feed ❤️ Thanks for tagging #archi_ologie Posted @withregram • @breathing_timemachine The Hackley House, Webster Ave, Muskegon, Michigan. Designed by David S. Hopkins, build 1887-1889. 

Mr. Hackley was born on January 3, 1837, at Michigan City, Indiana, the eldest of five children. When he was still an infant, his family moved to Kenosha, Wisconsin. At 19, he worked his way from Kenosha to Muskegon to join his father, who had been commissioned to build a sawmill along Muskegon Lake. 

He went to work shoveling sawdust into a boiler in the lumber yard of Durkee, Truesdale and Co. At a young age Hackley had learned office procedure and the basics of the lumbering business in the company store. 

Later on Hackley’s family followed him to Muskegon and founded the lumbering firm of Hackley and Sons. This later evolved into the lucrative partnership of Hackley and Hume. They had this and the Hume house constructed right next door to one another on Webster Ave. 

Hackley made a fortune of $18,000,000, one third of which he gave back to Muskegon. In 1888, he construction The Hackley Public Library. He served on the Board of Education of the Muskegon Public Schools for twenty years, was an alderman and a state delegate to two national Republican conventions.

Today, the Hackley and Hume homes are America’s finest examples of Queen Anne architecture.

Thanks for tagging #archi_ologie Posted @withregram • @retroroot This Queen Anne style house is located on D Street in Petaluma. Built in 1893 for Catherine Brown, who moved to town following her husbands death. The house features an oriel turret, porte cochere, and ornate grounds. repost via @instarepost20 from @victorian_vibes The Mistress. Trios Rivieres, Quebec. What a stunning and intriguing home! Love the little second floor balcony and shutter windows!! The dormer and it’s beautiful trim and detail! Those teeny arched windows!! The intricate facade and its stained glass!! Booked another part of our trip and we will be staying in this cute little town and this gem is only a stone throw away! Can’t wait to see these beauties in real life and stop my incessant obsession with creeping google street view 😆 Does anyone else do this or am I just a weirdo lololol can’t stop won’t stop! Also any recommendations for restaurants in Trois Rivieres would be so greatly appreciated!! 🙏🥂
